      <title>Re: Begging SOE to wake up.</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&amp;message.id=245978#M245978</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
Eq2SUCKS wrote:&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;***Kicking Moss Snake Memorial***&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Maybe because, unlike in sports, "successful" is relative. WoW is successful since it's the largest and most popular MMO on the planet right now. City of Heroes/Villains is successful because it's the largest and most popular MMO in its niche (non-fantasy, comics-genre). EQ1 is successful for neither of those things. It's successful because of its longevity. Tell me, how would you promote and advertise EQ to differentiate it from its more popular and well known competition? What does EQ have that WoW and CoH/V and and Anarchy Online doesn't have? Let's break it down some. AO has a "play for free" (not a trial, PLAY FOR FREE in its base world content, pre-expansion) option that makes it different. City of Heroes is targeted toward comic book fans. WoW has BLIZZARD behind it (along with all the positive goodwill, reputation, and tradition that goes along with it) along with over a hundred servers with localized versions in pretty much every major culture (i.e. the Aussies have their own server as does every timezone in the US and Europe and Asia), and servers bursting at the seams with population (people to group with!). The three games I mentioned have content for "time-starved" people (missions/quests, open zone hunting, etc) as well as for those with more playtime available to them (task &amp;amp; strike forces/trials, instances, group missions). EQ is a very good game but it doesn't have the same mainstream appeal as others on the market. And right now, the "others on the market" have more mainstream gaming options than EQ has. You cite Dungeons &amp;amp; Dragons Online obviously without knowing a thing about it. Name the two biggest MMO flops in 2006 so far? Auto Assault and......Dungeons &amp;amp; Dragons Online. Forced grouping (DDO) and limited content ("Do each mission 3 times") do not appeal to people when they have games like WoW as options. Do you think Turbine is adding solo content because they WANT to?!? Yes, I've played them all (from WoW all the way down to Hostile Space and SEED) and I can see why they shake out the way they do. &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;I've said it before, the market has spoken, and the market says "We don't want to have to play a great deal and need a number of other people's help to advance". I don't necessarily agree with that point of view (I've never been a time-starved type of gamer), but to ignore the fact that it has changed the MMO landscape from a business perspective would be moronic. WoW doesn't have 6.5 million people who play 4+ hours a day, 6 days a week. It's probably very much the opposite. You advertise EQ in a mainstream manner (i.e. via television) and you'll expose its warts while also showing you don't know what the market is demanding now. EQ is great in its niche and for folks who can devote the kind of time and dedication it requires to keep your head above water, so to speak. But EQ is not a mainstream gaming property anymore because the mainstream has moved beyond its borders. I'd go so far as to say ojier is more an example of mainstream than many folks in this thread. People just aren't willing to make life changes (even if its something as simple as emailing friends from the game to set up ingame meetings and events) to play some game. They want to log in and be able to DO something that appeals to them. Not sit around and wait to be picked for some event. I don't think EQ should be "WoWified" either since it's the only game of its kind currently on the market (that is, one that requires a fairly significant time investment and socialization skills to advance). IMO, there should be games available that appeal to ALL playstyles (whether PvE or PvP, casual or hardcore, raider or non-raider, killer or socializer, etc) and that's becoming the case slowly but surely. Folks who don't want to have to kill mobs to advance have games like SEED (where socialization is the key to advancement) and A Tale In The Desert (among others) to choose from. EQ is the Last of the Mohicans in this sense and thus, should not be changed to be more in line with WoW. That's what EQ2 is for IMO. That could also explain why EQ2 isn't performing as well as many folks might've thought. It launched head to head with the beast and had some technical issues that made it hard to compete with the juggernaught who couldn't open new servers fast enough to keep up with the demand.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;But I think advertising EQ on TV could do more harm than good. What happens when everyone in the world realizes that, relatively speaking, the Emperor has no clothes?&lt;BR&gt;&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
