..Dungeons &amp;amp; Dragons Online. Forced grouping (DDO) and limited content ("Do each mission 3 times") do not appeal to people when they have games like WoW as options. Do you think Turbine is adding solo content because they WANT to?!? Yes, I've played them all (from WoW all the way down to Hostile Space and SEED) and I can see why they shake out the way they do. &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;I've said it before, the market has spoken, and the market says "We don't want to have to play a great deal and need a number of other people's help to advance". I don't necessarily agree with that point of view (I've never been a time-starved type of gamer), but to ignore the fact that it has changed the MMO landscape from a business perspective would be moronic. WoW doesn't have 6.5 million people who play 4+ hours a day, 6 days a week. It's probably very much the opposite. You advertise EQ in a mainstream manner (i.e. via television) and you'll expose its warts while also showing you don't know what the market is demanding now. EQ is great in its niche and for folks who can devote the kind of time and dedication it requires to keep your head above water, so to speak. But EQ is not a mainstream gaming property anymore because the mainstream has moved beyond its borders. I'd go so far as to say ojier is more an example of mainstream than many folks in this thread. People just aren't willing to make life changes (even if its something as simple as emailing friends from the game to set up ingame meetings and events) to play some game. They want to log in and be able to DO something that appeals to them. Not sit around and wait to be picked for some event. I don't think EQ should be "WoWified" either since it's the only game of its kind currently on the market (that is, one that requires a fairly significant time investment and socialization skills to advance). IMO, there should be games available that appeal to ALL playstyles (whether PvE or PvP, casual or hardcore, raider or non-raider, killer or socializer, etc) and that's becoming the case slowly but surely. Folks who don't want to have to kill mobs to advance have games like SEED (where socialization is the key to advancement) and A Tale In The Desert (among others) to choose from. EQ is the Last of the Mohicans in this sense and thus, should not be changed to be more in line with WoW. That's what EQ2 is for IMO. That could also explain why EQ2 isn't performing as well as many folks might've thought. It launched head to head with the beast and had some technical issues that made it hard to compete with the juggernaught who couldn't open new servers fast enough to keep up with the demand.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;But I think advertising EQ on TV could do more harm than good. What happens when everyone in the world realizes that, relatively speaking, the Emperor has no clothes?&lt;BR&gt;&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;p&gt;Message Edited by HH-Silver on &lt;span class=date_text&gt;06-23-2006&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=time_text&gt;11:24 AM&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Ok let me get this straight , exposing Everquest to people who don't know about it is going to HURT the game because  the people that play it and are already addicted  will say hey , EQ has television advertisements and the graphics don't look that great on the television advertisements so im going to stop playing due to EQ having comercials ?&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;How exactly is EQ having advertisement going to HURT  Eq ?&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;your basically argueing for the sake of arguement as others have&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;your saying that EQ exists  because of its players and other games magically exist without having to depend on its player base  because ( i guess your logic goes)  people that play WoW  play because of the license and name behind it then quit and a constant surge of new people keep coming in and playing because of the license for a short pero